D-Cut on Qwen3.5-9B DFlash, Seq4096 / Out128
Summary
In the Qwen3.5-9B + DFlash A/B run with long-context profiling
(warmup_seq_lens=4096) and 128 generated tokens, D-Cut is neutral to slightly
slower at lower concurrency, but shows clear throughput and latency gains once
the batch is large enough:

c16: roughly parity / slight throughput loss.
c32: about +28% request throughput, +28% output-token throughput,
and 27% lower p50 latency.
c64: about +53% request throughput, +50% output-token throughput,
and 36% lower p50 latency.
This matches the expected D-Cut behavior: the controller adds small CPU/D2H
overhead, so it may not help at low batch, but it pays off at higher concurrency
where verifier compute dominates, especially with long multimodal-style
contexts.

Setup
Target model: Qwen3.5-9B
Draft model: Qwen3.5-9B-DFlash
Dataset: ALLaVA JSONL
Speculative method: DFlash
Speculative tokens: 15
D-Cut profiling sequence length: 4096
Output tokens per request: 128
Requests per arm / concurrency point: 256
Tested concurrency: 16, 32, 64
