Interpretation
D-Cut should be judged mainly at medium/high concurrency for this workload.
At c16, verifier compute is not yet dominant enough to amortize controller
overhead, so throughput is slightly below vanilla DFlash. At c32 and c64,
the long-context verifier cost becomes the bottleneck, and cutting the verifier
query length produces large throughput gains.

The TTFT result in this run is also favorable at higher concurrency:

c32: TTFT p50 improves from 0.21s to 0.17s.
c64: TTFT p50 improves from 1.10s to 0.74s.
This suggests that under high load, queueing and verifier cost dominate enough
that D-Cut reduces time-to-first-token as well, despite its per-step control
overhead.

Caveat
The captured output_log reports:

[warn] no D-Cut activation/profiling lines found in /tmp/qwen35_dcut_ab_9b_seq4096_out128/server_dcut.log
​
The performance shape strongly suggests the D-Cut arm behaved differently from
vanilla DFlash, but the report should not be treated as fully closed until the
server log also shows:

D-Cut adaptive verify ENABLED
VerifyAdaptiveController: cost table ready
profile  bs=... seq_lens=4096
​
The next rerun should keep VLLM_LOGGING_LEVEL=INFO enabled and attach the
D-Cut server check block to the result.

Conclusion
For Qwen3.5-9B DFlash under seq4096 / out128, D-Cut is promising at high
concurrency. The useful operating region starts around c32; at c64, the
measured gain is about +50% output-token throughput with substantially lower
latency. Low-concurrency results should not be used as the primary evaluation
point because D-Cut's controller overhead is not amortized there.
